  "summary": "Duplicate items",
  "environment_raw": null,
  "description": "If you put item in chest then having so much item on ground that cause the lag then shut down the app and log again the item you put in chest and your inventory still remain i found this bug in 1.21.5 n n",
  "Steps to Reproduce": "1. Create a new Survival world in Minecraft version 1.21.5.\n2. Gather at least 64 of any item (e.g., Stone, Dirt) and place them in your inventory.\n3. Find or create a chest and place it on the ground.\n4. Open the chest interface and place one item from your inventory into the chest.\n5. Drop a large number of items (at least 100) on the ground near the chest to create lag.\n6. Allow the game to lag significantly due to the number of items on the ground.\n7. Force close the Minecraft application while the game is still running.\n8. Reopen the Minecraft application and rejoin the same world.\n9. Open your inventory and check if the item you placed in the chest is still there, while also confirming that the item remains in your inventory.",
  "Environment": "Minecraft Java Edition Version 1.21.8",
  "Observed Behavior": "When the player places items into a chest while there are numerous items scattered on the ground, significant lag may occur due to the high number of entities. If the player then forcefully shuts down the application and subsequently reopens it, they may experience a duplication bug. Upon logging back into the game, the items that were originally placed in the chest will still be present in the player's inventory, in addition to the items that remain in the chest. This results in the player having two sets of the same items: one set in their inventory and another set in the chest. This bug has been consistently observed in version 1.21.5 of Minecraft. \n\n**Steps to reproduce:**\n1. Gather a large number of items and scatter them on the ground to create lag.\n2. Open a chest and place items into it.\n3. Forcefully close the Minecraft application while the game is still running.\n4. Reopen the application and log back into the same world.\n5. Check both the player's inventory and the chest to confirm that the items previously placed in the chest are still present in the player's inventory.\n\nThis issue could lead to unintended gameplay advantages, such as the ability to duplicate valuable items, and might require urgent attention from developers to maintain game balance and integrity.",
  "Expected Behavior": "When a player places an item in a chest and subsequently experiences lag due to a large number of items on the ground, the expected behavior is that upon restarting the game, the items in the chest should remain in the chest, and the player's inventory should reflect the items they had before logging out. Specifically, the game should save the state of the chest and the player's inventory independently, ensuring that the items stored in the chest are not duplicated or lost due to the lag or the app shutdown. This behavior aligns with Minecraft's design, where chests are intended to securely store items without interference from the player's inventory or the game's performance issues.",
